6. Split the dataset into the Training set and Test set. Choose your preferred split and justify the rationale.¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X_g10 = creditcard_g10.drop("Class", axis=1)
y_g10 = creditcard_g10["Class"]

#split the data into a 70% training set and a 30% test set. 
# Because the data is imbalanced, we must make sure that the training and test sets have the appropriate proportion of fraudulent transaction。
X_train_g10, X_test_g10, y_train_g10, y_test_g10 = train_test_split(X_g10, y_g10, test_size=0.3, random_state=random_seed)

print("X_train shape:", X_train_g10.shape)
print("X_test shape:", X_test_g10.shape)
print("y_train shape:", y_train_g10.shape)
print("y_test shape:", y_test_g10.shape)

7. Perform classification and compare the results.¶

In [ ]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, StratifiedKFold
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, BaggingClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier
import xgboost as xgb

# Setting random seed for reproducibility
random_seed = 2454
np.random.seed(random_seed)

#all alassfiers that we should use
classifiers_g10 = [
    LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000),
    KNeighborsClassifier(),
    DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    SVC(probability=True),
    GaussianNB(),
    RandomForestClassifier(),
    BaggingClassifier(),
    GradientBoostingClassifier(),
    xgb.XGBClassifier(eval_metric='logloss')
]

#cross validation with 5 folds
cv_g10 = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=random_seed)

def evaluate_models_with_cv(models, X_train, y_train, cv):
    model_scores = {}
    
    for model in models:
        model_name = model.__class__.__name__
        scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=cv_g10, scoring='accuracy')
        model_scores[model_name] = scores
        print("{} average CV accuracy: {:.4f}".format(model_name, np.mean(scores)))

    return model_scores

#get the accuracy scores for each model after cv
model_scores_g10 = evaluate_models_with_cv(classifiers_g10, X_train_g10, y_train_g10, cv_g10)
# I only choose one metric to evaluate the model, so I only use accuracy score.

LogisticRegression average CV accuracy: 0.9991
KNeighborsClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9983
DecisionTreeClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9991
SVC average CV accuracy: 0.9983
GaussianNB average CV accuracy: 0.9925
RandomForestClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9995
BaggingClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9995
GradientBoostingClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9990
XGBClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9996

# The box plots generated by Plotly do not show up after I generated the html, so I use seaborn to plot the boxplot.
def plot_model_scores_mpl(model_scores):
    df = pd.DataFrame(model_scores)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    
    #create the boxplot using Seaborn
    sns.boxplot(data=df)
    
    #set title, y-axis range, and rotate x-axis labels
    plt.title('Classifier Accuracy Distribution with Cross-Validation')
    # because the accuracy of the model is very high, I set the y-axis range from 0.992 to 1.0
    plt.ylim(0.992, 1.0)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)


    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

#show the plot
plot_model_scores_mpl(model_scores_g10)

The RandomForestClassifier, BaggingClassifier, and XGBClassifier show the highest cross-validation accuracies, all above 0.9995. GaussianNB has the lowest accuracy at 0.9925. Other models like LogisticRegression, DecisionTreeClassifier, and GradientBoostingClassifier perform closely, around 0.9991.

Select the best classifier for level 0 classifier.
Use logistic regression as a second level classifier.
Generate the box plot and show the accuracy of each algorithm as well as stacked classifier.
Also show the confusion matrices of the above algorithms .

In [ ]:
from sklearn.ensemble import StackingClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix


#models for stacking
#In all 9 models, LogisticRegression is one the best four models, so I choose other top 4 models to do stacking except LogisticRegression.
#We also need to use LogisticRegression as the final estimator, that is why I did not choose it.
selected_classifiers_g10 = [
    KNeighborsClassifier(),
    DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    SVC(probability=True),
    RandomForestClassifier()
]

#stacking ensemble with Logistic Regression as the final estimator
level0 = [
    ('knn', KNeighborsClassifier()),
    ('cart', DecisionTreeClassifier()),
    ('svc', SVC(probability=True)),
    ('rf', RandomForestClassifier())
]
stacked_model_g10 = StackingClassifier(estimators=level0, final_estimator=LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000))
all_models_g10 = selected_classifiers_g10 + [stacked_model_g10]

#because the insutrction said we do not plot metric that include accuracy, precision,recall, so I only extract the accuracy.
def evaluate_models_with_cv(models, X_train, y_train, cv):
    model_scores = {}
    
    for model in models:
        model_name = model.__class__.__name__
        scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=cv_g10, scoring='accuracy')
        model_scores[model_name] = scores
        print("{} average CV accuracy: {:.4f}".format(model_name, np.mean(scores)))

    return model_scores

#get cross-validated scores for selected and stacked models
all_scores_g10 = evaluate_models_with_cv(all_models_g10, X_train_g10, y_train_g10, cv_g10)

KNeighborsClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9983
DecisionTreeClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9991
SVC average CV accuracy: 0.9983
RandomForestClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9995
StackingClassifier average CV accuracy: 0.9995

The StackingClassifier performs comparably to the RandomForestClassifier, with slight differences in false negatives and true positives. While KNeighborsClassifier and SVC have fewer false positives, they underperform in identifying frauds (higher false negatives). The DecisionTreeClassifier misclassifies more genuine transactions (higher false positives) than the StackingClassifier. The StackingClassifier provides a balanced performance.

import pickle

#save model

    pickle.dump(stacked_classifier_g10, file)

10. Show both text and visual confusion Matrices using scikit learn and matplotlib and explain what the graph tells you and what you did.¶

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay

#calculate cm
cm_g10 = confusion_matrix(y_test_g10, y_pred_imported_g10)

#show text confusion matrix
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(cm_g10)

#show the cm
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8))
disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm_g10)
disp.plot(ax=ax, cmap=plt.cm.Reds)
plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
plt.show()

Confusion Matrix:
[[85283    11]
 [   30   119]]

85283 (True Negatives): This represents the total count of genuine transactions that the model accurately identified as such.

11 (False Positives): These are the authentic transactions that the model mistakenly flagged as fraudulent.

30 (False Negatives): These signify the actual fraudulent transactions that the model failed to detect and incorrectly labeled as legitimate.

119 (True Positives): This count denotes the instances where the model correctly pinpointed transactions as fraudulent.
